\par\par \b \uc2  Rupiah's fall - Who's responsible? \b0\par\par\uc2  By Ross H. McLeod \par \uc2 1,010 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 May 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  CANBERRA (JP): President Abdurrahman Wahid is blamed by many for Indonesia's deteriorating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance, which is already significantly worse than was expected when the current \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  was formulated. \par \par \uc2  The growth rate for 2001 has been revised down from 5 percent to about 3.5 percent. The average exchange rate has been revised upward from Rp 7,800 to Rp 9,600 per dollar, and the annual inflation rate from 7.2 percent to about 9.3 percent. \par \par \uc2  The last two of these performance indicators concern monetary management, however, which suggests that although the President makes a convenient scapegoat for this deterioration, we should not overlook the role played by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI), the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Maintaining the value of the rupiah is the responsibility of BI, as stated in its own law (Law No. 23 1999). This same law guarantees BI's independence: it cannot be told what to do by the government or any other party. If inflation and depreciation get out of hand, therefore, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  must bear the blame. \par \par \uc2  It is significant that the law provides only this single objective for BI. In other words, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not responsible for other aspects of macroeconomic management, which are left to the government. In reality, however, BI's board of governors has ignored the law and expanded the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's range of responsibilities. The result has been highly adverse for macroeconomic performance. \par \par \uc2  Specifically, BI has chosen to concern itself with two additional macroeconomic \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues: first, encouraging \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth; and second, holding down the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Its chosen strategy for achieving both objectives is to hold \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  down, by which it hopes to gain on at least three fronts. \par \par \uc2  First, businesses will not be discouraged by higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  from undertaking the new investment on which continued \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth depends. \par \par \uc2  Second, the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not expand by virtue of higher interest payments on floating interest rate government bonds used to recapitalize the banks. \par \par \uc2  Third, banks will not suffer the reduction in their capital adequacy that would result from falls in the market value of their holdings of fixed interest rate government bonds if \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  rose; this would require additional bonds to be issued, further increasing debt service costs in future budgets. \par \par \uc2  But BI appears to see a conflict between holding \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  down and the fulfillment one of its key commitments to the IMF: namely, to ensure a low rate of growth of the supply of base money (i.e. BI's monetary liabilities). \par \par \uc2  Faced with this perceived conflict, it has chosen to ignore its money growth commitment. Specifically, the government's most recent Letters of Intent to the IMF set a base money growth rate of 7 percent for 2000. \par \par \uc2  Extrapolating this into 2001 the target becomes Rp 94.2 trillion at the end of March, whereas the actual figure recorded was Rp 106.2 trillion - about 13 percent higher. \par \par \uc2  Yet the very reason for having this commitment is to ensure that BI meets its own legal responsibility to maintain the value of the rupiah: accordingly, BI's failure to meet it provides the main explanation for the steady increase in inflation over the last year or so. \par \par \uc2  In turn, rising inflation, together with the perception that BI has no clear idea of what it should be doing, has been causing yet another loss of confidence in the rupiah. This is resulting in currency speculation - over and above that caused by political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and poor leadership - hence the continuing weakness of the currency. \par \par \uc2  If BI chose now to abide by its commitment and bring base money back to where it should be, it would need to issue additional \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Certificates (SBI). This would require an increase in SBI \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which is where the apparent conflict between its legislated responsibility and its self-chosen responsibilities arises. \par \par \uc2  What a pity BI's institutional memory is so short! It needs only to look back to mid 1998, when output was falling and interbank \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and inflation were both running at around 70 percent to 80 percent, to see that its concern is misplaced. \par \par \uc2  From July 1998 BI suddenly began to control base money, reducing it by about 5 percent at first, and keeping its growth down to just 6 percent over the following 12 months. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  rose a little at first, but then fell dramatically to around 12 percent a year later. Growth did not fall. On the contrary, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  bottomed out in the second half of 1998 and then began growing quite strongly in 1999. \par \par \uc2  Inflation declined to a monthly rate below zero within just three months, and the rupiah recovered from Rp 15,500 to Rp 7,500 per dollar in much the same period. \par \par \uc2  If only BI had simply persevered with this highly successful monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , inflation would not now be above the double digit level, and the rupiah would be far stronger against the dollar. \par \par \uc2  It is real, not nominal, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  that matter to borrowers and depositors. Real \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are simply nominal \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  adjusted for expected inflation. The general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  have observed that inflation has been increasing steadily, and that rather than tightening up on monetary conditions to get back on track, BI simply adjusts its inflation target upward. \par \par \uc2  Thus depositors demand higher nominal \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to compensate for expected increasing levels of inflation, while borrowers are prepared to pay higher nominal rates, relying on inflation to reduce the real burden of their debts. \par \par \uc2  In short, BI's attempt to hold \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  down by increasing the money supply is failing because the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  itself generates expectations of inflation, pushing \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  up, not down. \par \par \uc2  Thus Gus Dur is not entirely to blame for rising inflation and the sagging rupiah. \par \par \uc2  The writer is Editor of the Bulletin of Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Studies, published by the Indonesia Project at the Australian National University in Canberra, Australia. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx5a000ge\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw2