\par\par \b \uc2  Government plans 30% hike in fuel prices this year. \b0\par\par\uc2 630 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 May 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The government may be forced to raise fuel prices by an average 30 percent this year in a bid to help maintain the 2001 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  at a safe level, Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Rizal Ramli said on Wednesday. \par \par \uc2  Speaking to reporters following a meeting with Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Rizal said that the price increase was a consequence of the plan to reduce the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  But Rizal was quick to say that the government would try to ensure that the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut would be mainly shouldered by the middle-to-high income earners rather than the poor. \par \par \uc2  The current state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  could widen to a dangerous level of 6 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) or nearly Rp 90 trillion (about US$8 billion), compared to the initial projection of 3.7 percent of GDP, primarily due to the sharp plunge in the value of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar and rising domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The government is planning several measures to try to limit the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to around 3.8 percent of GDP primarily by cutting \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  including the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and raising domestic revenue particularly \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The government plans to reduce the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by around Rp 5.6 trillion from Rp 41.3 trillion set under the current \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  But Rizal said that raising fuel prices was a very difficult choice because of the political and social consequences of the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "We want to fix the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  by cutting the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but we don't want to see a repetition of the May (1998) incident," he said, pointing to the social unrest that led to the downfall of former president Soeharto after he raised fuel prices in April 1998. \par \par \uc2  The government had earlier canceled the plan to raise fuel prices by an average 20 percent on April 1 due to the unfavorable political climate. \par \par \uc2  The government instead raised fuel prices for industries by between 50 to 100 percent, leaving the prices of kerosene and fuel products sold at gas stations unchanged. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, economist Didik Rachbini said that the time was not yet ripe for the government to raise fuel prices due to the current political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and weak purchasing power of the people. \par \par \uc2  "It is better for the government to focus on cutting \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the more prosperous provinces," Didik said. \par \par \uc2  The government has said that it plans to cut allocated funds for wealthier provinces and districts including by encouraging them to purchase government bonds, shares in state-owned enterprises, and assets under the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA). \par \par \uc2  The above measures are part of the plan to revise the current state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The revision will include the change in \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumptions including revising the rupiah rate to Rp 9,600 per U.S. dollar from an earlier estimate of Rp 7,800 per dollar, inflation rate to 9.3 percent from 7.2 percent, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth to 3.5 percent from 5 percent, and interest rate of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  SBI notes to 15 percent from 11.5 percent. \par \par \uc2  Rizal said that the revised state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be discussed at a cabinet meeting today before submitting it to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  for deliberation. \par \par \uc2  Rizal did not say when the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be submitted to the House, but Minister of Trade and Industry Luhut B. Pandjaitan said that it would only be made after the government held final discussions on May 16. \par \par \uc2  The House approval on the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  revision is a prerequisite demanded by the International Monetary Fund to decide on the disbursement of its next US$400 million loan tranche to the country. (rei) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx5a000he\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
