We have nothing but praise for the positive language spoken by Army Chief General Endriartono Sutarto when he warned President Abdurrahman Wahid against imposing martial law and dissolving Parliament as his response to the second censure issued by the House against him last month. Time and time again, the TNI has taken part in the national decision making process when it crushed several rebellions by separatists, communists, and discontented elements within the military who threatened to destroy the unity of the country. For President Wahid, the statement by General Sutarto could only have one meaning, that he should go about more carefully in doing his work as president lest he push the country into a ravine of misery and suffering. To try to preserve his position as president, he has tried to play with such far fetched and dangerous ideas as a dissolution of parliament, the holding of new elections or referendum and other things which boggle the mind. The question rises, why would Wahid choose the most intricate way of trying to save an already troubled position which has been causing him the loss of much goodwill among the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  rather than listen to his conscience by stepping down as president. We would like to assure him that Indonesia will not fall apart into pieces. Another thing that Army Chief Sutarto might not like is the idea of speaking to deaf ears. - The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  - STRAIGHTEN OUT \b \highlight22\uc2 SUBSIDY\b0 \highlight\uc2  FOR PEOPLE Our concern has finally been proven to be true. The disparity of prices of fuel oil for households, industries and mining activities has resulted in lots of "tremors", including the disappearance of several types of fuel, especially kerosene and diesel, in several cities. Look at the fuel prices which took effect on April 1. Diesel oil for mining activities costs Rp 2,300 per liter, same as in the market. Diesel oil for industries stands at Rp 1,150 per liter and that for households is Rp 600 per liter. This is ridiculous - the same product is sold in the same place but at completely different prices. Some people would take advantage of the situation so they would benefit from it. But how about those who have been accustomed to doing dirty business, such as smugglers? It would be more appropriate if the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is channeled to the education, health, and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation sectors. This \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  must trickle down to the people, not to "bad" businessmen. This would help the education sector, which has the most pitiable share of the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  compared to those of other Asian countries. This is a long-term investment. The people would be glad if the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is channeled to another sector to make them smart and healthy. If some disagree, their disagreement likely stems from those whose dirty business has been disturbed. - Media Indonesia \par \par \uc2  - TELKOM-INDOSAT LANDMARK DEAL Most of the independent shareholders, including foreign investors, predictably voted to approve the US$1.5 billion transaction between PT Telkom and PT Indosat, initialized in February to end their crossholdings in several telecommunications subsidiaries. The government, as the controlling shareholders in both publicly-listed companies, is correct in outrightly rejecting legislators request to postpone the shareholder meetings of the two companies and annul the deal to end their crossownerships. The transaction will remove \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about which company will control key mobile phone operators and how contracts to install new fixed-lines across the country will be resolved. This, will pave the way for foreign investors to enter the sector where foreign investment is crucial and settle speculation that Telkom and Indosat would be merged into a giant monopoly, something that has hampered investor sentiment in the industry. The role of telecommunications as a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  utility is so vital for a modern \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow that countries which fail to develop adequate telecommunications infrastructure will surely fall behind. Rapid technology changes that generate all kinds of innovative services can be made possible only by continuous investment and research, now extremely scarce in Indonesia. Hence, opening the telecoms market to foreign investors by creating level-field competition is the most effective way of accelerating the development of telecommunications in the country. - The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010709dx5b0022s\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
