itional suffering that will fall on the people with the series of price hikes, which will be set off by the planned increase of 30 percent in fuel prices, 20 percent in electricity and telephone rates and 2.5 percentage points in the rate of the value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the first half of next month. As the people are now putting up more sacrifices, it is the turn of Indonesia's international creditors, most notably the International Monetary Fund, which is leading a $5 billion bailout program for the country, the World Bank and Japan, to come up with their contribution to help the government and nation navigate through the sever turbulence ahead. This is surely another highly critical time in the life the nation, an emergency situation t hat calls for contingency measures on the part of Indonesia`s international friends. - The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010709dx5m001op\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
