\par\par \b \uc2  MONDAY 28th May 2001, EDITORIALS IN MAJOR INDONESIAN DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 725 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 May 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited.< Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its\par \par \uc2  POLITICAL BLACKMAIL In his desperate attempt to cling to power, President Abdurrahman Wahid has increasingly resorted to tactics such as threats, intimidation and political blackmail that have put the nation on a dangerous course. Abdurrahman has continued to entertain the idea of declaring state of emergency, solely to enable him to dissolve the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 . He also repeatedly claimed that six provinces would declare independence if he were removed from power. Whether these are prophecies or veiled threats, such statements have raised questions about the credibility of the President and about his commitment to the country and to the people who, through a democratic election, put him in power 18 months ago. Everyone realizes that Abdurrahman had a daunting and almost impossible task when he came to power in October 1999. Abdurrahman's record, however, has been disappointing to say the least. \par \par \uc2   He has failed to arrest the rot, and has even allowed the country to be pushed to the brink of collapse. He may be right in suggesting that Indonesia may be falling apart, but his prophecy will become self-fulfilling if he continues to deploy destructive tactics in order to cling to power. If that were really happen, God forbid, Abdurrahman might then be remembered as the President who initiated the final blow in Indonesia's destruction. - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  EVER WIDENING GAP The G-15 summit will open on May 30-31, 2001 on the same day as the House plenary session. The decision to choose Indonesia to host the 11th summit was made at the 10th summit in Cairo last year. Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri opened on Friday the conference of developing countries which started its preliminary talks of private sector inventors. In her opening address, Megawati expressed the hope that the meeting will bring about concrete results to the developing countries where hundreds of millions of people are still living in poverty. Despite all talks about inter-dependence and the pious words of government leaders in the advanced countries, we are witnessing today the ever-widening gulf of disparity between the rich and the poor countries as well as the rich and the poor within each developing country. \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  aid from the industrialized countries to Asia and Africa has failed to bring about improvement in the living condition of the poor people because quite a number of strings are attached to the aid, and many of the funds are regularly stolen by corrupt officials, which results in increased misery and financial burden. It is time the Western nations should waive repayment of debts which constitute a heavy burden on them. There can never be progress in this world if a small segment of people live like kings while the majority are destined to become carriers of water and cutters of wood. We would like to welcome presidents and delegates of the 11th summit of the G-15 to Jakarta and wish them success in their important work. - The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  REJECT TERRORISM AND POLITICAL ANARCHY When political tension escalates and members of the political elite are busy with their squabbling, it is always the people who feel the tension's impact. Advanced information technology has made it possible for regions to feel the heartbeat of the capital, Jakarta. Thus, the present political tension could quickly translate into violence in the provinces. The government has urged the people to stay calm and not be easily provoked into starting violence. Unfortunately, government officials, members of the political elite and religious leaders in the regions often make confusing statements that could add to the political tension, while the press have yet to give clear and transparent information. Some people, because of their limited knowledge of the real situation, are involved in terroristic and anarchic actions. Because of the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  political situation, they could easily be provoked into committing destructive actions. But for whatever reason, their acts could not be justified. In such situation, the security apparatus has to take stern measures. Those who commit violence should be punished. The perpetrators and their motives should be disclosed. Amid the difficult \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation, it sounds unfair to burden the people with more fears. All kinds of terrorism and anarchy should be eliminated, especially through the settlement of the political elite's own problems. - Media Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010709dx5s0026l\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Businessmen worried over heated situation. \b0\par\par\uc2 404 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 May 2001\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Businessmen are worried over the loss of their \par \par \uc2  foreign partners' confidence in the wake of the order made by the \par \par \uc2  President yesterday. They also refused to make major business decisions \par \par \uc2  pending improvement in the situation. \par \par \uc2  Textile businessman Indra Ibrahim said businessmen are worried that the \par \par \uc2  heated political conflict would undermine business activities. \par \par \uc2  "Ongoing orders are not a problem, but we are worried that buyers may see \par \par \uc2  prolonged \b \highlight22\uc2