\par\par \b \uc2  7 HOUSE FACTIONS RECOMMEND, 2 OTHERS OPPOSE SPECIAL MPR SESSION. \b0\par\par\uc2 840 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 May 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited.< Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its\par \par \uc2  Jakarta, May 30 (ANTARA) - Seven out of the ten factions in the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) at a plenary House session here Wednesday proposed the holding a special session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) to call President Abdurrahman Wahid to account. Two factions were opposed to the holding of a sepcial MPR session and one abstained. The seven factions in favour of a special session of the country's supreme \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  body represented the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDIP), the Golkar Party, parties grouped in the Reform Faction, the United Development Party(PPP), the Crescent and Star Party, the Moslem Sovereignty Party, parties grouped in the Indonesian Unity and Nationality Faction (FKKI). \par \par \uc2   The PDIP faction, the largest in the House, in its final review recommended the holding of a special MPR session on the ground that President Wahid had ignored the House's first and second memorandums as evident from the absence of any progress in his administration's performance. "The President has instead launched controversial statements deemed improper for a head of state," the PDIP faction spokesman, Sophan Sophian, said. In a similar vein, the Golkar faction spokesman said Abdurrahman Wahid's administration had been ineffective because the cabinet had only focused on how to save his presidency. The faction's spokesperson, Evita Asmelda said, there had been no significant progress in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as shown by the rise in the prices of basic necessities and a continuing decline in the composite index at the Jakarta Stock Exchange. About the Attorney General Office's finding that President Wahid was not involved in the Buloggate and Bruneigate financial scandals, Evita said the Office's probe had not been conducted transparently and would not affect the political process toward the holding of a special MPR session. The Crescent and Star Party (FPBB), through its spokesman, MS Kaban, said that during the four-month period after the issuance of the House' first memorandum, Gus Dur - as the President is popularly called-and his aides had been busy debating the legal basis for legislators to issue the memorandum. Instead of finding a solution, the President had created new controversies, Kaban said. The House last February 1 issued its first memorandum to President Wahid to warn him over the poor performance of his administration after concluding there was strong reason to believe he had played a role in Buloggate and Bruneigate. Considering that Wahid had yet to respond to the first censure, the House issued its second memorandum on April 30, again warning him to improve his administration or it would initiate proceedings toward his impeachment. \par \par \uc2  Political deadlock The Moslem Sovereignty faction (FPDU) in its final review said that an MPR special session was the best solution to the current political deadlock between Gus Dur and the House. The faction noted that instead of paying heed to the House memorandums, Gus Dur launched the idea to issue a decree to dissolve the parliament. Meanwhile, the Reform faction based its proposal for an MPR session on the fact that Gus Dur's response to the House's second censure had prompted vertical as well as horizontal conflicts which could lead to the nation's disintegration. "All the President's efforts to find solution, both in the form of cabinet reshuffle and power sharing have failed to resolve the leadership crisis in the country," the faction's spokesman, Ambia Bustam, said. The United Development Party faction called on President Wahid to stop making controversial statements and issuing policies not beneficial to the people. The Indonesian Unity and Nationality faction (FKKI) said a special MPR session would not automatically result in Gus Dur's ouster but it would be an effort to seek the best solution to the country's political crisis. \par \par \uc2  Two factions against Two factions, namely the Nation's Awakening Party's and the Love the Nation faction (FPDKB), rejected the proposal to call for a special MPR session, while the National Defence Forces (TNI)/National Police (Polri) faction neither supported nor opposed the idea to hold a special MPR session. FKB spokesman Ma'ruf Amien did not explicitly reject a special MPR session but called for a peaceful solution to the conflict between the parliament and the President for the good of all. "People are waiting for legislators' wisdom as they have been living in hardship and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and now hope to have a better future," Amien said. The faction also called on the legislature to renounce its allegations that Gus Dur was involved in the Bulog and Brunei scandals. The FKB said the nation should avoid using unfair means to fight injustice because otherwise new complicated problems would arise. The TNI/Polri faction said it would be neutral and accept any decision taken by the House plenary session. The faction noted that both the military and the police would not involve themselves in politics and urged all people to be prepared to make sacrifices in the nation's best interest. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010709dx5u002eo\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
