\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Economy \highlight\uc2  amid political crisis. \b0\par\par\uc2 710 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 June 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  There is good reason for the market to weather the next two months of heightened political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  with a lesser sense of foreboding despite the potentially explosive situation and the ongoing leadership crisis. Though the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  has given a vote of no confidence in President Abdurrahman Wahid - making his government a lame duck and a new government widely expected after the Aug. 1 Special Session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) - there are strong indications that the ailing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not be entirely cut adrift. \par \par \uc2  The first factor, which reassures us that the potentially disruptive period until August will largely be kept under control without new grave incidents or violence, is the increasing self-confidence and professionalism on the part of the National Police and the military. \par \par \uc2  The highly professional manner and cool-headed tactics with which the security forces acted to avert major incidents during the massive demonstrations by Abdurrahman's supporters before and during the House plenary session on Wednesday assures us that the next turbulent period would most likely pass without devastating violence. \par \par \uc2  The surprisingly relative calmness, despite repeated threats of massive violence, is quite reassuring to businesspeople, indicating that they will be able to conduct business as normally as possible in the specially vulnerable circumstances Indonesia is now mired in. \par \par \uc2  Even though foreign investors will remain on the sidelines, waiting for the resolution of the leadership crisis, the favorable developments over the last few days should convince businesspeople overseas to continue trading deals with Indonesia. Foreign tourists also will not likely wipe the country completely off their list of destinations. \par \par \uc2  The ability to maintain law and order will undergo its most severe test, especially within the next two months, when the last round of the political battle between the President and \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  body will take place and threats of massive demonstrations and worker revolt will be greatly pervasive with the plans to raise fuel prices and electricity and telephone rates later this month. \par \par \uc2  It is also comforting to note that the House, after a rowdy, marathon plenary session on Wednesday, immediately resumed on Thursday its \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  duties related to the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Irrespective of the vote of no confidence in the President, the House finance and \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  commission resumed deliberations with finance minister Prijadi Praptosuhardjo on the planned amendments to the 2001 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  This assures us that despite the differences between the House and the President they remain united and cooperative with each other when it comes to the nation's interests. \par \par \uc2  We are now confident that even though the national political agenda will likely be dominated by preparations for the upcoming MPR Special Session, the House, the members of which also make up 500 of the MPR's 700 members, together with the government will push ahead with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform agenda to strengthen the budding recovery. \par \par \uc2  This collaborative stance is quite pivotal because there are several reform measures, already far behind schedule, that have to be approved shortly for implementation. Among them are the planned amendments to the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  law. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  amendments are especially quite urgent as the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year is already in its second half. Further delays would make the special measures less effective in achieving the targets set in the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  amendments, thereby threatening the government with an unmanageable \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  with its devastating repercussions on the macroeconomy. \par \par \uc2  The government-proposed amendments to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  law also requires immediate completion to dispel any doubt about the political independence of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  that has been stipulated in the 1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  law. \par \par \uc2  Few would argue the vital importance of an independent, autonomous \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially now amid the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and leadership crisis. This independence will assure the business community and the general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  that the monetary sector will not be vulnerable to short-term political interests. \par \par \uc2  So all in all despite the turbulent political condition, we can still rest assured that the decision-making process in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which directly affects the common people, will not stall but will continue to run, although perhaps not as full-fledged as needed to cope with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in view of the leadership crisis. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx62000uy\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{