\par\par \b \uc2  SATURDAY June 02 2001, EDITORIALS IN INDONESIA'S MAJOR DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 950 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 June 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited.< Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its\par \par \uc2  ERRATIC RESHUFFLE President Abdurrahman Wahid may have been exercising his constitutional prerogative in reshuffling the Cabinet on Friday, but he still owes the nation a logical explanation as to why he made those changes. Unfortunately, his explanation after the announcement fell short of expectation, and, with regards to the dismissal of Coordinating Minister for Political, Social and Security Affairs Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, it raises more questions than it gives answers. For those who find it increasingly difficult to make any sense out of Abdurrahman's recent policies, bear in mind that we are dealing with a president whose middle name is erratic. Susilo has been a key figure in Abdurrahman's Cabinet for much of the past year as the President faced growing pressure to step down. \par \par \uc2   A retired three-star Army general and a highly capable and competent administrator, Susilo has always come across as a loyal and dependable, yet independent, figure in the Cabinet, earning him the respect of supporters as well as critics of the President. His presence lent credence to the administration at a time when the President's own credibility and popularity were rapidly waning over allegations of corruption and misrule. Susilo's departure represents a tremendous loss to the President Abdurrahman. The Cabinet increasingly looks more like a bunch of yesmen, depriving the President of the wisdom and the experience of able and competent figures like Susilo. - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  WHO IS RESPONSIBLE As the dust lifted from the debris and rubble caused by vandalism carried out by supporters of President Abdurrahman Wahid in various towns in East Java, to put an end to what they call a conspiracy against their leader, it was reported that 150 people went missing, presumably killed in the disorder. For weeks in the run up to the start of the Parliament session which on Wednesday agreed to hold a combined special session of the MPR on August 1 to decide on the political fate of President Wahid, a systematic campaign has been going on in towns in East Java, which are considered strongholds of the Nahdlatul Ulama (NU) to defend their leader. A new group of young militants has been formed who are ready to kill for their ideals. Party leaders in East Java should from the very beginning try to cool down these hot fanatics who in their unbridled fanaticism might create havoc and chaos. Instead, they keep on issuing statements supporting the conspiracy that elements of the New Order are ready to take over, for which it is imperative to liquidate the power of President Wahid. It is a pity that they get the impression that fighting for democracy means hiding a sharp weapon under your shirt and chanting Qur'an verses and hating enemies who are trying to force Wahid to resign. - The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  IRRATIONAL MOVE President Abdurrahman Wahid may now in deep trouble but he is still capable of showing his power. In the name of a cabinet reshuffle, he fired several ministers. But his move, especially by dismissing Coordinating Minister for Political, Social and Security Affairs Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, has invited a big question. Is the reshuffle intended to improve the cabinet's performance? The answer: absolutely not. The reshuffle seems to be just an effort by Gus Dur to maintain his power with any authority still left although he himself is facing another big problem, namely loss of credibility. This can be perceived from National Police Chief General Surojo Bimantoro's refusal to resign. His rejection was supported by 30 provincial police chiefs all over Indonesia. Common sense tells us that, in such this situation, Gus Dur must create a calm situation, instead of triggering controversies and antagonisms. We believe that imposing martial law is a constitutional authority of the president. However, it can be only executed if the nation is really in chaos. Thus, it would be very funny if the President suddenly announced martial law while the situation in the country is still normal. Now a number of new ministers have been appointed. It is quite difficult to understand why there are still persons who want to become ministers of a government which will last only two months. - Media Indonesia \par \par \uc2  POSITIVE SENTIMENTS DISAPPEAR The market gave a positive response when Abdurrahman Wahid was elected president and his cabinet formed in October 1999. But as things developed over time, Wahid's administration proved unable to meet people's expectations. Since Wahid became president, political conflicts escalated causing nervousness in the market, leading to negative sentiments which automatically affected the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The rupiah's exchange rate which used to hover at the level of Rp7,000 against the US dollar, weakened progressively. The continuous depreciation saw the rupiah tumble to Rp9,000 and eventually penetrate the level of Rp10,000 and even Rp11,000. What happened on Friday proves that we are still far from the end of the political fighting. We are again to be plunged into a period of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , following the move of President Wahid to replace several ministers in his cabinet. The market has already given a response to the latest development. The rupiah which had been strengthening during two days, yesterday weakend by 190 points. The composite index decreased by 9.3 points, causing the index to plunge below 400 points. Millions of people are still in need of jobs. Meanwhile, the people are also burdened by increasing cost of living, including telephone, clean water, fuel, electricity prices, and value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Still it seems we don't consider all this homework as a priority. We still give preference to political matters and power. - Kompas. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010709dx62002m6\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  'RI must sacrifice if it wishes to end ties with IMF'. \b0\par\par\uc2 564 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 June 2001\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Former government official reminded \par \par \uc2  that the government would have to sacrifice a lot in \par \par \uc2  terms of the consequences it must bear if it wishes to \par \par \uc2  free itself from the IMF. \par \par \uc2  Bambang Sudibyo, former finance minister, reminded the \par \par \uc2  decision to be free from the IMF equates letting go of \par \par \uc2  other multilateral institutions related to the IMF. \par \par \uc2  According to him, the delayed US$400 million loan from \par \par \uc2  the IMF is much to small compared to other loans \par \par \uc2  offered by other multilateral institutions. \par \par \uc2  "If we want to be free from the IMF, the government \par \par \uc2  must be prepared to lose around Rp120 trillion. Under \par \par \uc2  this condition, is the government ready for it," he \par \par \uc2  asked yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Bambang cited two multilateral institutions related to \par \par \uc2  the IMF, CGI and Paris Club. He calculated that the \par \par \uc2  government has to be prepared to lose US$5.2 billion \par \par \uc2  per year from the CGI and US$5.8 billion from the \par \par \uc2  Paris Club. The Paris Club helps reschedule offshore \par \par \uc2  loans, which matures March 2002. \par \par \uc2  "My opinion, under the cu