\par\par \b \uc2  Currency analyst sees rupiah constrained by political moves. \b0\par\par\uc2 818 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 June 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): President Abdurrahman Wahid's move last week to fire a number of Cabinet members will likely reverse the rupiah's upward movement against the U.S. dollar, currency analysts say. \par \par \uc2  Currency analyst Martin Pangabean said Abdurrahman's recent reshuffling of his Cabinet had caused worries that he would go ahead with his plan to declare a state of emergency. \par \par \uc2  "The market did not see it (the reshuffle) coming," he told The Jakarta Post on Friday, adding that the created \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  had eroded confidence in the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah has been on a upward trend since the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 ' plenary session on April 30 opened the way to the President's impeachment at the upcoming People's Consultative Assembly's special session. \par \par \uc2  The session, set for August, is expected to dispel the fog over the country's future leadership when the President is asked to present his accountability. \par \par \uc2  Analysts believe a change in the country's leadership would at least create more confidence in the country's ailing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Last week the rupiah ended at 11,325 against the U.S dollar, up from the previous week's closing at 11,450. \par \par \uc2  But rumors of a sudden Cabinet reshuffle just before the market closed on Friday pushed the local unit down from Thursday's closing at 11,130. \par \par \uc2  Ahead of the long weekend, investors were also seen stocking up on dollars to factor in more political surprises. \par \par \uc2  Martin said that while he could not see any potential upsides for the rupiah, there was no immediate reason to unload the local unit just yet. \par \par \uc2  "The market needs time to absorb what has just happened," he said. \par \par \uc2  President Abdurrahman said that the Cabinet reshuffle was an attempt to bridge the gap with his ally-turned-opponent Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri, who has publicly expressed her readiness to take over the top job. \par \par \uc2  Former communications minister Agum Gumelar was appointed as coordinating minister for political, social and security affairs, replacing Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, whom the President once said had the potential to replace him. \par \par \uc2  Speculation rose that Susilo was dismissed for his refusal to impose a state of emergency, under which the President could dissolve the House and thereby get rid of his political opponents. \par \par \uc2  With the appointment of Agum, the President hopes to reverse the unfavorable developments. \par \par \uc2  Agum has close ties with Megawati, and once led the Army's Special Force (Kopassus), suggesting his influence over the military. \par \par \uc2  With the military distancing itself from the President, his threats against legislators almost ring hollow. \par \par \uc2  The President also lost the support of the police after his move to suspend National Police chief Gen. Surojo Bimantoro. The police are standing behind Bimantoro in his refusal to step down at the President's order. \par \par \uc2  Legislators said that by law, any reshuffling in the National Police must have House approval. \par \par \uc2  Friday's Cabinet reshuffle also saw the dismissals of Sarwono Kusmaatmadja as the minister of maritime affairs and fisheries, and Marzuki Darusman as the attorney general. The former was active in Golkar, the latter is currently the party's deputy chairman. \par \par \uc2  Marzuki was replaced by Baharuddin Lopa, a human rights advocate who also opposes corruption. \par \par \uc2  According to Martin, the appointment of Agum and Lopa boost the chances of reconciliation between the President and his deputy. \par \par \uc2  "The market wants to see what breakthroughs these two men can achieve," he went on to say. \par \par \uc2  However, Martin continued, selling pressure could arise from corporate demand. A thin dollar supply also makes the rupiah prone to steep falls. \par \par \uc2  "The market is thin, corporate demand could send the dollar to 12,000," he warned. \par \par \uc2  Currency observer Rico Menayang said on Monday that with the current political development, most market players would sideline the local currency market. \par \par \uc2  According to him, fears of inflation could trigger corporate rupiah selling in exchange for dollars needed to import raw materials. \par \par \uc2  May inflation rose by an alarming 1.13 percent on top of a declining export revenue needed to replenish the local dollar supply. \par \par \uc2  Rico said the drop in exports was partly because of fewer dollar-denominated investments made, which would have otherwise enabled manufacturers to maintain production levels. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, capital market observer Dandossi Matram said the market index would fall slightly as a result of Friday's Cabinet reshuffle. \par \par \uc2  "If it (the index) falls, I don't think it will go lower than 380," Dandossi said. \par \par \uc2  He said that after the Cabinet reshuffle, President Abdurrahman had few options left to surprise the market. \par \par \uc2  "There are only two ways he could surprise us: declaring a state of emergency or announcing his resignation," he said. \par \par \uc2  He estimated trading would be flat this week, with the potential of the index recovering to 400. The Jakarta Stock Exchange Composite Index closed last week's trading at 396.51, up from 390.12. (bkm) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx65000wd\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal447