\par\par \b \uc2  Jakarta's informality aides the poor. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Marco Kusumawijaya \par \uc2 1,298 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 June 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): You may laugh at this, but it is true: Jakartans are forbidden by law to play in any \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  spaces except for those determined by the governor. \par \par \uc2  So far, strangely enough, no one has inquired about the list of approved \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  spaces. Mind you, also forbidden is a habit that Indonesians have become so accustomed too, namely, collecting donations from among colleagues in an office for someone who is getting married or has a relative that just died, unless, that is, the governor's approval has been obtained. \par \par \uc2  It is also a must, by law, for Jakartans to walk only on the sidewalks where streets have been provided with these. When you have a traditional massage in your office, you must not forget to ask if the masseur has a permit from the governor, because it is expressly forbidden to practice any form of traditional medicine without it. \par \par \uc2  These bizarre rulings are all contained in the amusing Jakarta Bylaw No. 11 of 1988 on \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  order. This is the same law that forbids street vendors from plying their wares and becak (pedicabs) from operating on our streets. It consists of 33 articles of which 22 start with "It is forbidden to...". It is this law that provides the basis for the annual "operation" by the city's \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  order department to evict street vendors, so that for years they have been unable to organize themselves for lack of certainty about their continued existence. \par \par \uc2  This, in turn, has led to them having a bad image, and being accused of messing up the city and disturbing \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  order. This is the law that provides the legal basis for the "maintenance of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  order" \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  that has recently been the subject of claim and counterclaim by the police and the city's \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  order department. What a shame! \par \par \uc2  For Wardah Hafiz's Urban Poor Consortium and dozens of organizations representing street vendors, it has been the cause of a perpetual struggle with the city's \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  order department. \par \par \uc2  But the law does not only concern the poor. For one, by a reasonable estimate at least 70 percent of office workers along Jl. Thamrin and Jl. Sudirman depend on the vendors for their lunches. \par \par \uc2  For another, looking at the articles it contains, the law is in fact a totalitarian, unilateral condemnation of all informal activity in the city. It is born out of a twisted idea about "urban development" and "modern" urban life. \par \par \uc2  Behind the scenes \par \par \uc2  The year 1988 marked the height of the repressive New Order regime. It marked the launch of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  liberalization. The mission of the then-governor Wiyogo Atmodarminto, a former Indonesian ambassador to Tokyo, was to attract investors. Jakarta, therefore, had to look "clean" and "formal". Everything "informal" was deemed untidy and had to be erased. But, as we frequently see today, it has only increased the number of conflicts because it represents nothing more than a mindless effort to impossibly sterilize the appearance of the city. It attempted to place every aspect of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  life under the control of the local authority. \par \par \uc2  In this time of crisis, more conflicts may be expected to occur. For, obviously, the number of self-employed, entrepreneurial street vendors will rise in direct proportion to the (formal) unemployment rate. So, there will also be more preman (street thugs), hooligans, and desperate low-paid civil servants. \par \par \uc2  With political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and little hope in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  arena for at least the next five to 10 years ahead, informality can be turned into an asset and enable many poor Jakartans and Indonesians in other cities to survive. Jakarta and its surrounding districts are, for example, witnessing the growth of healthy urban agriculture all over the place. \par \par \uc2  By contrast, however, the new Jakarta master plan governing the capital's development up to 2010 has reduced the 'formal' allocation of land for urban agriculture to less than 200 hectares located in one location only - near the airport - as compared to thousands of similar places in the old master plan. \par \par \uc2  This is despite the fact that urban agriculture is saving thousands of poor families from going hungry and forging collaboration between different socioeconomic classes - middle-income owners of vacant urban plots and low-income urban kampong dwellers. \par \par \uc2  Urban agriculture also provides Jakarta with reasonable quality food without costly and polluting, long-distance motorized transport. It also improves microclimates and the soil structure of the vacant land. Agricultural areas at the urban fringes can be designed as greenbelts to avoid uncontrolled urban sprawl. It can be combined with recreational as well as some nature conservation functions such as water retention and flood buffer zones. \par \par \uc2  Mixed land use increases infrastructure efficiency, while also providing the cheapest mode of combining productive and housing activities for the urban poor (and, actually, for everybody else), as long as environmental health is heeded. \par \par \uc2  Historically, this is how cities have always been. That's how it should be. It is the twisted idea of the "modern", radical separation of working and living that has ruined the concept. It is now a good time to shift the paradigm because of today's additional conditionality: the need to survive the crisis. \par \par \uc2  This indeed provides a good reason - a better one than the lobbying of some land-hungry businessmen - to propose a revision of the spatial plan. \par \par \uc2  Rejection of informality has been the enemy of the urban poor for the last 30 years. An international workshop titled Coping with Informality and Illegality in Human Settlements in Developing Cities was held from May 23 to May 26, 2001, in Leuven, Belgium, as a milestone marking the end of the old paradigm and the start of one that sees informality as a space for accommodating the complexity of a sustainable popular \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and as a necessary source of healthy plurality in urban life. \par \par \uc2  For three decades the previous paradigm has failed, and produced an ever-increasing frequency of conflict, which is becoming too expensive and unbearable for Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Anticipating more difficult times to come ahead, it is very reasonable, and actually urgent, for Indonesian cities to consider policies which are more inclusive of informality. \par \par \uc2  Revisions of urban development plans, including land-use plans, need, at the very least, to be effected. This must be coupled with a more pro-poor mass transport system. The United Nations Covenant on Social \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Rights - unfortunately not yet ratified by Indonesia - demands that housing be located where access to employment is easy. \par \par \uc2  For the poor and their informal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , it also very obvious that their survival depends on proximity to the more formal economies of the middle and upper classes. Therefore, isolating them from the latter will deal the deathblow to them. Malls and white-collar workplaces need to provide space to accommodate them. \par \par \uc2  Middle-and upper-income housing estates are also the natural sources of employment and livelihood for them. Proximity and access as between the different income groups should be designed to make symbiosis possible. \par \par \uc2  Simultaneously, the local authority might, perhaps, turn its attention to other forms of informality that proliferate among the rich. If \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  order officers were to just look around, they would quickly spot kitchens and front porches extended beyond the allowed building lines, or driveways extending out into \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  rights-of-way, houses being illegally used for all sort of businesses, garbage being dumped in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  spaces, including toll-road tickets discarded five meters after the exit gate. \par \par \uc2  After all, can we really say that the notorious practices of corruption, collusion and nepotism are not the product of an "informal" attitude among the members of the elite in managing \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  affairs? \par \par \uc2  - The writer is an architect and urbanist based in Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx6h0019l\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Manufacturing shares gain 4.34%. \b0\par\par\uc2 211 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 June 2001\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA: Trading of the manufacturing shares throughout the 7/6 to 14/6 \par \par \uc2  period was bullish. Investors were cautiously hunting the already cheap \par \par \uc2  blue \par \par \uc2  chips. Investors' sentiments grew more and more positive as the special \par \par \uc2  parliamentary session nears, especially with a relatively calm political \par \par \uc2  situation last week