\par\par \b \uc2  Gus Dur to go ahead with Australian visit on Sunday. \b0\par\par\uc2 325 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 June 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): President Abdurrahman Wahid will go ahead with his visit to Australia and two other countries this week, Minister of Foreign Affairs Alwi Shihab announced on Monday. \par \par \uc2  Speaking to journalists after the induction of five new Indonesian ambassadors at the State Palace, Alwi contended it was impossible to cancel the trip, as the President had repeatedly postponed his visit to Australia. \par \par \uc2  "The President can no longer postpone his trip to Australia on June 24, because he rescheduled his planned visit there five times in the past," the minister said. \par \par \uc2  Australia was among the first countries Abdurrahman planned to travel to when he became president in October 1999. \par \par \uc2  However, domestic opposition to the trip, particularly from legislators, forced him to postpone his previously scheduled visits. The last cancellation was in early April. \par \par \uc2  Last week, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said he welcomed Abdurrahman's plan to visit despite the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  he faced at home. \par \par \uc2  He praised the planned trip as proof of Abdurrahman's genuine intent to bolster ties between Jakarta and Canberra. \par \par \uc2  Ties between the two countries were jarred in late 1999 following the events which transpired in the former Indonesian province of East Timor. \par \par \uc2  Alwi said on Monday that during the trip to Australia, the President would discuss a general array of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues. \par \par \uc2  "There are several things which need to be followed up," Alwi said. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, Wahyu Muryadi, presidential protocol bureau chief, said the President would only bring a small entourage with him to Australia because of \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  limitations. \par \par \uc2  He said the President would stay a few days in Canberra and several other cities in Australia before flying to Christchurch in New Zealand, where he was scheduled to stay for one night. \par \par \uc2  "On the way back to Jakarta, the President will make a brief stopover in Manila on June 30," Wahyu told The Jakarta Post. (prb) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx6j0019w\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Investment in oil, gas down drastically.    \b0\par\par\uc2 975 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 June 2001\par \uc2  Bisnis Indonesia \par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2  (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia \par \par \uc2  Investment in oil and gas explorations drastically    took a plunge in the first quarter of the year, as riots and political    \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the first quarter of this year drove investors away from    \par \par \uc2  here.    \par \par \uc2  Pertamina senior official Iin Arifin Takhyan said investment in the first    \par \par \uc2  quarter of this year (oil and gas only) could reach US$870 million.    \par \par \uc2  The first four months of last year saw companies crossing the fingers, as    \par \par \uc2  investment in the sector stood at US$2 billion last year.    \par \par \uc2  "Production-sharing companies are counting their days and mulling over the    \par \par \uc2  future of Indonesia," he said here yesterday.    \par \par \uc2  Iin, who was accompanied by Pertamina senior official Abubakar Siddick    \par \par \uc2  Nitikusuma, added that the drop in investment counts as one of the lowest    \par \par \uc2  in the history of foreign investment in oil and gas.    \par \par \uc2  "We had envisioned a revenue of US$5,8 billion this year," he said.    \par \par \uc2  Besides politics and security, the Pertamina director also mentioned the    \par \par \uc2  few numbers of oil wells developed by production sharing companies (KPS)    \par \par \uc2  as the reasons behind the poor investment in oil and gas.    \par \par \uc2  This year, he said, the target to develop oil wells has been set at 1.031    \par \par \uc2  units.    \par \par \uc2  "Up to the first quarter only 15% or 161 units have been developed."    \par \par \uc2  He lamented the fact that most oil wells to be developed are in the KPS    \par \par \uc2  area controlled by PT Caltex Pacific Indonesia.    \par \par \uc2  "At the same time Caltex is being plagued by social-political issues in    \par \par \uc2  the forms of unrest and blockades."    \par \par \uc2  He also cited the fact that talks on extending the contracts over the    \par \par \uc2  Coastal Plains Pekanbaru (CPP) - managed by Caltex-are moving slowly.    \par \par \uc2  Iin added that Beyond Petroleum (BP Indonesia) - through BP Kangean-has    \par \par \uc2  postponed its investment plan worth US$300 million.    \par \par \uc2  BP Kangean, he said, initially wanted to develop the offshore oil well at    \par \par \uc2  Blok Terang Serasun in Madura.    \par \par \uc2  "BP indicated that it wants the contract extended as the old contract    \par \par \uc2  expires in 2010."    \par \par \uc2  However, said Iin, the government has yet to approve that idea.    \par \par \uc2  "Extending a contract that has yet to expire could leave the government    \par \par \uc2  and Pertamina open to accusations of corruption, collusion, and nepotism,"    \par \par \uc2  he said.    \par \par \uc2  Vice President Corporate \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs of Caltex A. Haidar Makki    \par \par \uc2  confirmed that last year unrest, blockades and pilferage saw the largest    \par \par \uc2  KPS reduce production by 40.000 barrels per day or 5% of its total    \par \par \uc2  production. (eh) The IMF hoped it could normalize ties with    