\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty \highlight\uc2  to further hurt banking industry - Analysts. \b0\par\par\uc2 629 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 June 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will further drag down the ailing banking industry, economists have warned. \par \par \uc2  Eugene Keith Galbraith, an independent commissioner at Bank NISP, said here on Wednesday that the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  had failed to provide a necessary direction for local banks to cope with their financial hardships. \par \par \uc2  He said that a series of reshuffles in the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team had often put business players in the dark as each minister tended to have different priorities in managing the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Such \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  should be removed if the government wants to see the banking industry fare better in the future," Galbraith said after Bank NISP's annual shareholders general meeting. \par \par \uc2  In the meeting, the bank's shareholders approved the appointment of Michael J. Higgins as new commissioner representing International Financial Corporation, and Surjawaty Tatang as a new director. \par \par \uc2  Galbraith said the reshuffles, especially in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team, were too frequent and had made the government lose its momentum in coping with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems, as can be seen in the continued fall in the rupiah to the U.S. dollar. \par \par \uc2  He acknowledged that although the rupiah was greatly affected by nonfinancial factors, such as the country's political conflicts, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  should also be responsible for the weak rupiah. \par \par \uc2  He said that the rupiah's continued decline had forced the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to push up \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in a bid to prevent the currency from further falling. \par \par \uc2  Banks have had no choice but to follow the high interest rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  although such moves caused a severe blow to their operations, he said. \par \par \uc2  "With high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , banks cannot execute their intermediation function properly to provide loans for businesses," he added. \par \par \uc2  In such a situation, it would be difficult for the banks to stand on their own feet, although many had received a capital injection, albeit only in the form of bonds, from the government. \par \par \uc2  He said the current gloomy situation had also discouraged foreign investors from joining the country's banking activities. \par \par \uc2  "The policies confuse foreign investors about where the government really wants to go," Galbraith said. \par \par \uc2  Amitava Banerjee, an IFC representative for Indonesia, said that the country's weak legal system also discouraged investors from entering the local banking industry. \par \par \uc2  "This is a very important issue for investors," he said after the meeting. \par \par \uc2  IFC is one of Bank NISP's institutional shareholders, with a 9.61 percent holding. \par \par \uc2  Citing an example, Banerjee said the cancellation of Standard Chartered's purchase in Bank Bali in 1999 indicated the weakness in the country's legal system. \par \par \uc2  Therefore, the government should speed up the legal and judicial reform to encourage both local investors and foreign investors to the banking industry, he added. \par \par \uc2  Bank NISP president Pramukti Surjaudaja said that the bank projected an unconsolidated net profit increase of between 10 percent and 20 percent this year from Rp 36 billion in 2000. \par \par \uc2  He said the bank planned to extend Rp 1.5 trillion in new loans this year, 80 percent of which would be channeled to small and medium-sized businesses, and the remaining 20 percent would go to consumer financing. \par \par \uc2  The fresh loans would raise its total credit outstanding by 50 percent to Rp 4.5 trillion at the end of this year, from about Rp 3 trillion at the end of 2000, Pramukti said. \par \par \uc2  The bank also plans to open between 10 and 20 new branches in Jakarta, Bogor, Tangerang, Bekasi, Bandung and major cities in Sumatra this year. \par \par \uc2  Parwati Surjaudaja, the vice president of Bank NISP, said that the bank had budgeted between Rp 500 million and Rp 2 billion to establish a new branch. (05) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx6l001en\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
