\par\par \b \uc2  Economist warns inflation in 2001 may surge to 14%. \b0\par\par\uc2 709 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 June 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Inflation in 2001 could reach a worrying level of around 14 percent, much higher than the government forecast of 9.3 percent, due to a combination of the country's slower export performance and the recent increase in fuel prices and electricity rates, senior economist Suhadi Mangkusuwondo said on Friday. \par \par \uc2  Suhadi said that slowing exports could hit the country's foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which would in turn weaken the rupiah and trigger a cost-push inflation. \par \par \uc2  "Inflation in 2001 could surge to 14 percent particularly due to slower export performance," he told reporters during a gathering held to discuss the results of the latest Pacific \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Outlook (PEO) for 2001/2002. \par \par \uc2  After registering a record 16.1 percent in export growth last year, the country's exports this year are expected to weaken significantly due to slower \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the U.S. and other trading partners. \par \par \uc2  Suhadi explained that much higher inflation could further undermine the rupiah and trigger a higher interest rate environment, which would present a severe threat to the still weak banking sector. \par \par \uc2  "Let's just hope this will not happen," he said. \par \par \uc2  A weaker rupiah against the U.S. dollar would push up production costs as the country's production system depends heavily on imported raw materials. \par \par \uc2  The government has spent billions of dollars to recapitalize the country's banking sector, though it is still in danger of falling into a second crisis as the rising domestic interest rate is applying serious pressure on the margins and will present further difficulties in restructuring bad loans. \par \par \uc2  The benchmark interest rate of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's one-month SBI promissory notes is currently hovering at 16.55 percent. The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has said that it would maintain its tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  amid inflationary pressure. Some bankers have said that if the SBI rate reaches 18 percent, certain banks will start to suffer negative \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) had earlier warned that inflation could reach double digits if the rupiah continues to weaken due to domestic political instability. \par \par \uc2  The increase in fuel prices by an average of 30 percent this month and electricity rates by 20 percent next month would also contribute to higher inflation, said economist Arie Kuncoro, who is also active in making the PEO forecast. \par \par \uc2  On the rupiah, Arie said that the local unit was expected to hover at an average rate of Rp 9,750 per U.S. dollar this year, slightly weaker than the government's forecast of Rp 9,600 per dollar. \par \par \uc2  He said that even with a change in the country's leadership, the rupiah would not get much stronger than it did when President Abdurrahman Wahid took over power in late 1999. \par \par \uc2  He said that this was mainly due to the huge demand for dollars to repay foreign debts particularly by the country's corporate sector. \par \par \uc2  "Even if there's a political settlement, we won't see a significant recovery in the exchange rate of the rupiah. The rupiah won't strengthen to the Rp 9,000 per dollar level or higher," Arie said. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah is currently hovering at around Rp 11,355 per dollar. The weakening of the rupiah is partly due to domestic political instability as embattled President Abdurrahman Wahid is facing the risk of being impeached by the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), the country's highest \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  body, which plans to hold a special session on August 1. \par \par \uc2  Suhadi said that the PEO has forecasted that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will grow by 4 percent this year, lower than last year's 4.8 percent growth, will grow by 5.5 percent in 2002, assuming that a resolution to the country's political problems has been reached later this year. \par \par \uc2  "The downside is much greater," he said. \par \par \uc2  Suhadi said that if domestic political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  continued, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2001 would be much lower at 3 percent. \par \par \uc2  "The slower \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance will create a vicious circle. On the one hand, political stability could be achieved if there's stronger \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance, but on the other hand, to achieve stronger \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, political stability is vital," he said.(rei) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx6n001gp\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
