\par\par \b \uc2  Stalemate prevents recovery. \b0\par\par\uc2  By James Castle \par \uc2 1,168 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 July 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Businessmen are normally hesitant to make their political views \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but there is little doubt that the long running political stalemate between President Abdurrahman Wahid and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) has had severe \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  consequences. \par \par \uc2  While the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  performed relatively well last year, this was primarily due to a benign international environment and a continuation of the V-shaped rebound which usually follows such large drops like Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  experienced in 1998. It is fair to say that last year's growth was not due to improved policies and performance. \par \par \uc2  It happened despite the lack of attention to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in either the administration or the DPR because of the intense focus on the political struggle between the President and his opponents. \par \par \uc2  This year the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has slowed dramatically, revealing the lack of a clear national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  or any serious attempts to pursue such a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Indeed, how can any \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continuity or effective implementation be expected, given the ministerial merry-go-round to which the country has been subjected over the past several years. \par \par \uc2  Since May 1998 there have been four coordinating ministers for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , five coordinating ministers for political affairs, four finance ministers, five heads of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) and an equal number of changes in posts of critical importance to business and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery such as the minister of energy and mineral resources, minister of manpower, President of Pertamina, etc. \par \par \uc2  It is clear to business as well as the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  at large that these frequent changes have not been made on performance grounds but rather in response to the various political imperatives, as the government struggles to survive attacks from its numerous political foes. \par \par \uc2  The effects of this stalemate can be felt everywhere. The man in the street feels the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  decline most directly in rising prices and the decline in job opportunities. Unemployment increases and social tensions rise. Government planners and politicians suffer because they have been forced to watch their carefully-crafted 2001 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  fall apart under the onslaught of rising prices, higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and ballooning government \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The collapse of the government's original \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  has also increased tensions between the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  planners and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and now threatens the entire international bail-out package. \par \par \uc2  At the beginning of this year, the IMF agreed to fund a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  equal to about 3.5 percent of gross domestic product. Once it became clear the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  would exceed 6 percent of GDP, or more than US$8 billion, the IMF balked. \par \par \uc2  Not only did it indicate it would not increase its financial support to fill the wider gap, it also said it would not supply the amount originally agreed upon because the government did not deliver on its promise to limit the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to 3.5 percent. \par \par \uc2  The passage of a new \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  by the DPR has removed this roadblock and renewed talks with the IMF are underway at this moment. \par \par \uc2  To business observers, it seems like the country's leaders have gotten themselves into a deadly trap. Because the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not recovering, political tension has increased and support for the current government has declined. \par \par \uc2  Conversely, the increase in political tension and the decline of support for the current leadership both in the administration and in the DPR has further eroded \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence, causing investors to defer activities. \par \par \uc2  The breakdown in communication and, more important, the loss of respect between the DPR and the President has made it impossible to implement the few policies the government has tried to pursue, even those agreed upon with the House. \par \par \uc2  Routine decisions, well within the scope of executive authority, taken in implementing policies approved by DPR, are subject to review, renegotiation, vicious attack and de facto vetoes. The most glaring business example in this regard, is the inability of investors to close deals with IBRA even after they have paid their money. Cases like Manulife insurance and the Guthrie plantation deals have poisoned the atmosphere. The current lack of interest in the sale of BCA shares is a clear indicator of the real cost of the political intrigue and \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stalemates which have plagued IBRA since its inception. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, business watches helplessly while politicians trade accusations and parliament threatens to remove the President from office. While individual businessmen have their favorites, there is no consensus in the business community as to whether President Abdurrahman Wahid or Megawati Soekarnoputri would be the better person to lead the country and promote \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  One suspects this political agnosticism is primarily because the current political struggles seem more based on the desire for power for its own sake and the right to name colleagues and cronies to important and powerful positions, rather than to promote any particular \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  agenda or \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ideologies or principles. \par \par \uc2  In the wake of such an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  political climate, investors are keeping their money in their pockets. Businesses are reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to absolute minimums. The biggest worry in the business community is that the current leadership struggle will end in yet another stalemate rather than produce a decisive result. \par \par \uc2  Many observers talk about seeking a win-win situation. Unfortunately, politics rarely offers win-win solutions. It is in the nature of democratic politics that one side wins and the other loses, at least until the next election when a past loser may indeed become a winner. It is vitally important for the current political struggle in Indonesia between the President and the DPR to produce a clear and decisive winner. \par \par \uc2  It is also important that the loser acknowledge and accept defeat, knowing that it may be his or her turn again in 2004 or an earlier election should the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) so mandate. If a clear winner does not emerge, it is highly unlikely that any new government formed in the wake of this debilitating process, be it a new Megawati government or yet another revised Abdurrahman government, will have the necessary power and support to pursue a strong \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery program. \par \par \uc2  If a new stalemate results, one can expect more \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  drift, a further decline in the rupiah value, higher inflation and increasing political dissatisfaction, insuring that the next government will have an equally short life. On the other hand, if a decisive winner is produced with a clear mandate to attempt to lead the country out of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  morass, we can anticipate a market honeymoon, a strengthening rupiah, a decline in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , a contracting \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and an ultimate turn around of Indonesia's devastated \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  There is little the investor can do at this point. The initiative and the power is now in the hands of the politicians. It is time for them to put the nation's interests ahead of their own. \par \par \uc2  The writer is a technical advisor at PT Jasawenang Citrasempurna, a subsidiary of the Castle Group. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010730dx76000nz\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
