\par\par \b \uc2  September deadline for LoI 'difficult to meet'. \b0\par\par\uc2 767 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 July 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The September deadline for the signing of a new lending agreement between the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the government may prove to be difficult to meet, as \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  lingers over the life span of the current government, economists warned. \par \par \uc2  University of Gadjah Mada economist Sri Adiningsih said the impending People's Consultative Assembly special session may result in a new lineup of economics ministers. \par \par \uc2  "It's only natural that the IMF would first want to ensure the commitment of the new team before they resume their lending to Indonesia," she told The Jakarta Post over the weekend. \par \par \uc2  She said the possible change in the government was most likely the reason why the IMF only went as far as agreeing on a draft of the lending agreement. \par \par \uc2  The government initially expected to sign the final letter of intent (LoI) by last week, however only a draft was completed. \par \par \uc2  The final LoI will contain a set of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform targets, which Indonesia must meet in order to obtain the fund's loan. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's poor record of meeting the targets contained in the current LoI caused the IMF to freeze a US$400 million loan tranche last December. \par \par \uc2  The government and the IMF have said their priority is to sign a new LoI before the Paris Club meeting in September. \par \par \uc2  Failure to do so would put at risk the debt rescheduling agreement between Indonesia and its sovereign creditors under the Paris Club. The meeting is slated for the first week of September. \par \par \uc2  The Paris Club agreed to reschedule $2.8 billion in debts this year, on the condition that the government sign a new LoI with the IMF by March. Because the LoI was not signed, the group is now free to collect the debts anytime this year. \par \par \uc2  There are concerns that the IMF will delay discussion of the LoI until after a new government is formed, Sri said. \par \par \uc2  The Assembly's special session in August looks certain to lead to the removal of President Abdurrahman Wahid. \par \par \uc2  Sri said that should a new government emerge, the IMF would likely send a team to Jakarta to seek a commitment on the new LoI, in what could be another time-consuming process. \par \par \uc2  "The IMF's stance will depend on the lobbying power of the new economics team," she said. \par \par \uc2  Sri added that the new economics team should be able to pick up immediately the work of its predecessors. \par \par \uc2  And there are further time constraints, with the IMF scheduled to take a recess starting next week until Aug. 22. \par \par \uc2  Nonetheless, Sri said that even if Indonesia missed the September deadline, it would not necessarily spell disaster. \par \par \uc2  "I don't think September is a set target, it's negotiable. If the government can come up with the right reasons, the Paris Club will understand," she said. \par \par \uc2  However, economist Dradjad Wibowo of the Institute for the Development of Economics and Finance said neither the IMF nor the government could afford to miss the deadline. \par \par \uc2  "If missing the deadline leads to a negative note from the Paris Club members, this will be counterproductive for the IMF itself," he warned. \par \par \uc2  He said the country members of the Paris Club would want to prevent providing \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  for writing off Indonesia's bad debts. \par \par \uc2  But should they demand payment, it would send Indonesia teetering toward bankruptcy, he said. \par \par \uc2  "Higher \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and another fuel price hike to raise more money are out of question," Dradjad said. \par \par \uc2  Defaulting on the payments on domestic bonds is also unlikely because that would harm the banking sector, whose earnings rely on government bonds, he added. \par \par \uc2  Dradjad said this situation would tempt Indonesia to default on the payments on its foreign debts, a move the IMF would not be pleased with. \par \par \uc2  "But this would be the best of the bad options," he said. \par \par \uc2  Separately, Minister of Finance Rizal Ramli continued with his anti-IMF rhetoric, urging for reforms in the institution. \par \par \uc2  "The IMF has misdiagnosed (\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  illnesses) in many developing countries, causing their crises to deepen," Rizal was quoted as saying by Antara news agency during a book launch last Friday. \par \par \uc2  He said the IMF's most damaging mistake in Indonesia was the imposition of a "super-tight" monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which led to the country's banking crisis. \par \par \uc2  Rizal has been lashing out at the IMF since he took his previous post as the coordinating minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  His stance contributed to the friction between the IMF and the government following the suspension of the IMF loans. (bkm) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010716dx7g0000d\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
