\par\par \b \uc2  BPEN pessimistic on government's 2001 export target. \b0\par\par\uc2 551 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 July 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  10 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The National Agency for Export Development (BPEN) said on Thursday the government's 2001 non-oil and gas export target of US$51.3 million would be difficult to meet given the weak export performance in the first five months of the year. \par \par \uc2  BPEN chairman Gusmardi Bustami said non-oil and gas exports between January and May decreased by 0.09 percent to $18.6 billion, compared to the same period last year. \par \par \uc2  "Frankly speaking, it will be hard to achieve the non-oil and gas export target for this year," he said during a media conference on the preparations for the 2001 Export Products Expo, or 2001 PPE. \par \par \uc2  He said his pessimism was also based on the fact that export orders, which customarily are made six months in advance, were now mainly made between only one or two months in advance due to political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the country's security problems. \par \par \uc2  The government has said it expects 2001 non-oil and gas exports to increase by 7.5 percent to $51.3 billion from $47.7 billion last year. \par \par \uc2  But Gusmardi said the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown in the U.S. and political instability at home had negatively impacted the country's export industry. \par \par \uc2  "Non-oil and gas exports may increase but not by (7.5 percent)," he added. \par \par \uc2  Gusmardi said he hoped new President Megawati Soekarnoputri could bring stability to the country, an important element needed to boost exports. \par \par \uc2  "If stability continue to exist, I have no doubt that the rupiah will be stronger ... that's good for export industry," he said. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah has soared to a five-month high of about Rp 9,775 per U.S. dollar following the appointment of the country's new President. \par \par \uc2  Gusmardi said the stronger rupiah would help reduce exporting companies' costs, because most of their raw materials and machinery were imported. \par \par \uc2  For example, textile companies import 70 percent of their raw materials, footwear firms 70 percent and electronics companies 80 percent, he said. \par \par \uc2  He also hoped a more positive situation in the country would be followed by lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which would enable companies to repay debts and receive loans at more affordable rates. \par \par \uc2  A turnaround in the U.S \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would also help Indonesia's exports, he said. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, Gusmardi said the 2001 PPE, which will be held from October 24 to October 28 at the Jakarta Fairgrounds in Kemayoran, had received a positive response from both the country's exporting firms and foreign buyers. \par \par \uc2  He said about 1,191 producers and 879 foreign buyers had confirmed that they would take part in the expo. \par \par \uc2  "We're optimistic that 1,241 firms and 6,000 foreign buyers will participate in this expo," he said, adding about 4,800 buyers took part at last year's expo. \par \par \uc2  Companies at the expo will display such items as furniture, handicrafts, textiles, footwear, foods and beverages, and leather, metal and rubber products. \par \par \uc2  "We expect that the transactions at this year's expo will increase by between 15 percent and 20 percent to $120 million from $103 million last year," Gusmardi said. \par \par \uc2  He guessed that furniture, handicrafts, wood products, electronics and leather products would dominate the transactions at the expo.(05) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010727dx7r00060\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picsc