\par\par \b \uc2  A tale of two systems in city transportation. \b0\par\par\uc2 907 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 August 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  This is the second of two articles on transportation in Jakarta by Heru Dewanto, who heads the Center for Technology and Industry Development. He is also CEO of the Jakarta-based Rekainfra International company which is among the consultants involved in the city's mass transit project. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The subway on the other hand would rely on government \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and other government support. Yet, the main source of income would come from the farebox and this should cover 60 percent of total revenue. The remainder would be from government indirect \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  These \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  were planned to be achieved primarily from a road pricing scheme for private car users along the Blok M in South Jakarta to Kota in West Jakarta corridor. These revenues would be exclusively earmarked for financing the mass rapid transit (MRT) system in the form of government \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Other sources of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  could be obtained from other \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 : betterment \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  for properties along the corridor, fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , car ownership \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , parking charges. Again, these \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be channeled to fund the subway as government \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . In addition, there are land development potentials to be incorporated in the investment structure. This is different from toll roads investment, for instance, that may not include property development in their investment schemes. \par \par \uc2  On top of those \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government would still have to provide other support measures such as guarantees for soft loans, exemptions from import duties and provision of hedging against foreign currency risks. The bottom line is that a huge investment of this kind requires government involvement in many ways. \par \par \uc2  To minimize costs, the combination of three different structures was explored - a system of underground, road surface and elevated structures. Costs were to be cut to about one-third of the funds needed for the original plan, though this meant compromising on visual intrusion, traffic distraction during construction and the other negative impacts of an elevated structure. \par \par \uc2  The political crisis added to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  turmoil has led to further \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding these projects. Jakarta \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation finds itself in a dilemma - while \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation has been neglected and left to deteriorate due to poor maintenance, the system must nevertheless carry the city's commuters operating at only a fraction of its capacity. \par \par \uc2  Despite having completed studies and designs and obtaining all the required approvals, implementation is another story. So is the crisis solely responsible for holding up the progress? \par \par \uc2  Learning from those initiatives, it is quite obvious that the fundamental structure of mass transit investment has not been put in place. Each tries to overcome the financial shortcoming by developing its own approaches that in many cases may not be based on transportation rationales or best practices. There is no such standard \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of investment structure on mass transit yet. \par \par \uc2  What next? \par \par \uc2  The important question is whether Jakarta's mass transit development has ended with the crisis and, if not, how it can bounce back. The options are simply do-nothing or do-something. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slow down actually offers an opportunity to re-assess and reformulate the structure of mass transit investment. Such a cost-minimum preparation should have been undertaken over the last three years. \par \par \uc2  The real benefit is that when the crisis is mitigated and the country starts to bounce back, the infrastructure will be ready to support growth. On the contrary, delay would lead to the transportation infrastructure further hampering \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Further delay would prove to be very expensive. Obviously we have missed three valuable years in a do-nothing option. \par \par \uc2  The do-something option should have covered the following issues. There is a need to improve the balance of risk between government and private sector. There is a need to provide more equal competition between the rail and the road by, for example, internalizing the externalities. This means, for instance, road pricing and betterment \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the landlords within the area concerned, property development, parking and telecommunications along the corridor. \par \par \uc2  A mechanism for earmarking these pricing policies and \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  needs to be prepared. What is mostly needed is a new robust and integrated pricing \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  applied to the transportation sector and also to other related sectors. \par \par \uc2  Assessment of potential funding schemes should be extended to other government undertakings and multi-sources funding support from the government. Further government commitment and support in the form of \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be required to integrate the mass transit with other \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation services, including bus rerouting. Likewise, concurrent land use \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is badly needed. \par \par \uc2  This conducive environment should be applied to other infrastructure, whether in the form of toll roads, power and water facilities or others. The city and the country cannot afford to repeat the old approach: moving on with huge projects that are often associated with flaws, yet based on a fragile and unsustained basis. \par \par \uc2  The mass transit system and infrastructure as a whole desperately needs new approaches based on a more sustained and efficient basis. A consensus among the government, private sector, users and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  is needed to agree to a new principle of approaches in the provision of mass transit. This consensus could be achieved through the setup of a city transportation council. \par \par \uc2  This can be followed by changes in the legal and regulatory framework. \par \par \uc2  Finally, we would agree on one thing: In a few years Jakarta must begin work on its first mass transit system. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010806dx830002e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
