\par\par \b \uc2  Market expects Hamzah to deliver on his promise. \b0\par\par\uc2 778 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 August 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): As the country enters its third week, effectively without a government, the rupiah's rise and fall hinges on whether Vice President Hamzah Haz can deliver on his promise to present a "market friendly" Cabinet this week. \par \par \uc2  Currency analyst Farial Anwar said the market was expecting President Megawati Soekarnoputri to heed its demand for a professional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team. \par \par \uc2  Hamzah said last week that President Megawati would pay special attention to her \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team, which he said would have the respect of the market. \par \par \uc2  "Megawati had better not disappoint the market, once it loses confidence in her, she won't get it back easily," Farial told The Jakarta Post over the weekend. \par \par \uc2  Already the new president has tested the market's patience with the absence of a working Cabinet despite the pressure to bring the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  back on track. \par \par \uc2  Megawati was supposed to announce her Cabinet last Friday, but decided, for reasons still unknown, to postpone the announcement to next Thursday. \par \par \uc2  The decision frustrated the market, as signs of an intensifying struggle for key posts in the Cabinet became more apparent. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah fell slightly to 9,640 on the news as against 9,600 the previous day. \par \par \uc2  However, the stock index took the news badly causing it to plunge to 436.46 from 443.13 the day before. \par \par \uc2  Observers were divided over the impact of the delay in the Cabinet's announcement, with some claiming it was to ensure a stronger Cabinet, while others warning of political interests infesting key posts. \par \par \uc2  Despite the lingering \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the Cabinet, the rupiah ended higher last week at 9,500 compared to 10,000 the week before. \par \par \uc2  "We saw the rupiah strengthening although the government had not even begun its work, so don't lose this optimism," Farial said. \par \par \uc2  Dealers said \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  might have lend a hand by intervening on Friday, to take advantage of the thin trading that day. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor Sjahril Sabirin said the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  was ready to intervene if necessary. He also said the delay in forming the Cabinet would only have a temporary negative impact on the market. \par \par \uc2  "In the longer term, the market will realize that a stronger Cabinet was more desirable," he said. \par \par \uc2  Farial said the rupiah still had room for gains should the long wait for a Cabinet prove to be worthwhile. \par \par \uc2  "It's still possible to get to 9,000 on a good \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team," he predicted. \par \par \uc2  He said the market would then watch the International Monetary Fund (IMF)'s reaction to the new government. \par \par \uc2  "The IMF's response is a benchmark for the international market's confidence," he explained. \par \par \uc2  He said a positive signal from the IMF would be an immediate disbursement of the long delayed US$400 million loan tranche. \par \par \uc2  On the stock market, traders remained wary over President Megawati's seeming indecisiveness. \par \par \uc2  Stock analysts Dandossi Matram said the market had grown impatient over Megawati's failure to announce the Cabinet lineup on time. \par \par \uc2  He said even if Megawati presented a market friendly \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team, it could only bring about a minor boost to the stock index. \par \par \uc2  According to him, the market had already capitalized on Megawati forming a strong Cabinet when she was elected into office. \par \par \uc2  Should Megawati's Cabinet fall in line with market expectation, the index may rise to about 450, Dandossi estimated. \par \par \uc2  "The index will rebound to the market's earlier expectation when Megawati became president and everyone expected a stronger government," he said. \par \par \uc2  Megawati rose to the presidency on Monday, July 23. It pushed the index to 470, but it quickly slid to 450 on profit taking the following days. \par \par \uc2  Dandossi cited 450 as reflecting the market's real expectation of Megawati and her new Cabinet. \par \par \uc2  Last Friday, the Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) Composite Index ended the week's trading at 435.15 as against 447.39 the week before. \par \par \uc2  He added that a still gloomy \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook and sluggish regional market capped further growth. \par \par \uc2  Last week the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) issued a slew of disappointing data, citing year-on-year inflation for July at an alarming 13.4 percent. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's concerns over high inflation rates and a weak rupiah landed investors with discouraging high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "But \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not the main issue here as all \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators depend on political stability," Dandossi went on. \par \par \uc2  Megawati's priorities should be on political, security and legal certainties to allow the inflow of foreign investment, he said. \par \par \uc2  "Political certainty will stabilize the rupiah, lower banks \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and in turn encourage investment," he explained.(bkm) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010