\par\par \b \uc2  TUESDAY Aug 7 2001, EDITORIALS IN MAJOR INDONESIAN DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 618 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 August 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.\par \par \uc2  LOCALIZING INVESTMENT LICENSING Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) chairman Theo F Toemion took the right approach and demonstrated a thorough understanding of his mission when he asserted a meeting with domestic and foreign businesspeople last week that he is working to turn the board from a regulatory into a market-driven servicing agency. The situation has now dramatically changed, however, especially after the establishment of regional autonomy early this year. BPKM can no longer centralize the licensing of investment in Jakarta and should instead delegate most of its authority to local administrations. BPKM should assist local administration and local legislatures, which produce local regulations, to fully comprehend that attracting investment to their areas in the most effective way of creating new sources of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue and developing local \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2   A new investment or business will create jobs, which means providing local people with purchasing power and consequently generating private consumption from which local administration can collect various levies or service charges imposed. Further down the track, an area with a rapidly developing business sector will post the highest increase in the market value of local property and this turn will raise proceeds from property \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , 80 percent of which belongs to local administration. We are looking forward to seeing local administration complete keenly with each other in attracting investment to their areas by pursuing market-friendly policies and enacting business-friendly regulations. - Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  A TEST FROM RIAU President Megawati Soekarnoputri is facing a heavy test. While she has yet to finalize her cabinet lineup, the people of Riau province have strongly rejected the presidential decree she has issued extending PT Caltex Pacific Indonesia's contract on the management of the Coastal Plains Pekanbaru (CPP) oil block. The case of the CPP oil block is a matter of justice. The people of Riau have recently demanded a fair share of the profit from the oil block. If that is the root of the problem, the soluion should lie in the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  distribution mechnism instead of transferring the ownership of the asset to certain individuals. If the province controls the company, the seeds of corruption will only be spread across the country. What will happen is not equal distribution but injustice. The basic solution in the CPP oil block case is \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , not the transfer of ownership and management. With \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the local government could gain democracy. And only with \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  could regional autonomy preserve the spirit of unity from Sabang to Merauke. - Media Indonesia \par \par \uc2  DEBTS WILL NOT CRUSH THE RUPIAH The pressure on the rupiah has eased. Several factors have contributed to this. First, the narrowing down of the political rift. Controversial Abdurrahman Wahid has been dismissed from the presidency, while his successor, Megawati Soekarnoputri, is expected to bring fresh air to Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political recovery. Second, the International Monetary Fund will come to Indonesia this August, earlier than the original schedule of September. Third, the demand for foreign exchange has declined. Nonetheless, we should not yet rejoice because the country's debts are still huge. The total amount of debts which should be paid this year is US$ 33.2 billion, inclding US$ 7.3 billion in government debts. Such a huge amount could put pressure on the rupiah. However, other threats might also come from the political condition in the country. The delay in the announcement of the cabinet has hampered the strengthening of the rupiah. The country's debts have yet to pose a threat to the exchange rate of the rupiah. But \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in political and security affairs would prevent the rupiah from strengthening and becoming more stable in the long term. - Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010810dx870005l\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  RI proposes Paris Club III. \b0\par\par\uc2 285 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 August 2001\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The government is thinking of proposing to the \par \par \uc2  consortium of creditors the Paris Club III meeting in order to alleviate \par \par \uc2  the debt burden of Indonesia, said senior economics minister Dorodjatun \par \par \uc2  Kuntjoro Jakti. \par \par \uc2  He noted that Paris Club I and II - they both agreed to reschedule debts \par \par \uc2  worth US$4.2 billion and US$5.8 billion which matured between 1998 and \par \par \uc2  March 2002-were not enough to reschedule debt repayment. \par \par \uc2  "Paris Club should get priority as we deal with the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said \par \par \uc2  here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Djatun, however, is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  whether Paris Club III would merely discuss \par \par \uc2  rescheduling or debt relief in the form of haircut. \par \par \uc2  Djatun said the focus of Paris Club meetings should be \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2  sustainability as part of the overall program to recover the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Finance Minister Boediono earlier said the government would first deal \par \par \uc2  with Paris Club II before entering Paris Club III. \par \par \uc2  Djatun cited other nations' experience, especially cases related to \par \par \uc2  Panama, Venezuela, Uruguay, Argentina, and Chile. \par \par \uc2  Early this week Australia and the World Bank said they would study \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's foreign debt structure. \par \par \uc2  The government owes US$140 billion as of 2000 (including domestic debts), \par \par \uc2  up from US$56 billion before the crisis. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia obtained rescheduling accords in Paris Club I and II, but that \par \par \uc2  is not seen as the answer to the problem as it only shifted the burden to \par \par \uc2  the future. \par \par \uc2  So far the government and the IMF have alleviated the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  by \par \par \uc2  slashing \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which in effect transfers the burden to the people in \par \par \uc2  the form of rising prices of fuel and electricity. \par \par \uc2  The senior \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  minister also urged all, including political parties, \par \par \uc2  to support the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery program. (01). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010813dx8a00001\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Paris Club III said not to discuss debt relief. \b0\par\par\uc2 245 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 August 2001\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Paris Club III is said not to be planning to discuss \par \par \uc2  neither debt relief nor debt reduction over Indonesia, said an economist. \par \par \uc2  "That is impossible as that is not the solution